<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>1</title></head><body><div><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:-0.15pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by </span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">University College London (WSC029)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The following response to the House of Common Select Committee Inquiry into </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">women in STEM careers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> is</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> from University College London. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">Why do </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">you think the number of women in STEM academic careers decline further up the career ladder?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Biases:</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Unconscious </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">or conscious </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">biases could also be a significant factor </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">–</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> there have been several studies looking at the biases of interview panels, and the peer review process</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> These research projects often involve p</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">anels being given identical CVs</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">with</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> obviously gendered names. In these studies, women are less likely to be</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> considered of equal standing, less likely to be offered a position and if they are offered a post they are offered a lower salary than male applicants. This questions the basic assumption of meritocracy that pervades academia. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">When women do choose to con</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">tinue within science, and apply for positions, they might encounter barriers to their progression </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">through the biases of interview, promotion or peer review </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">panels. The fact that academics in STEMM subjects are often men means that female academics are ofte</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">n interviewed by all male panels. There is well documented evidence that people often unconsciously select people who are like themselves </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">–</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> which means that departments </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">continue</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> to replicate the white, middle class, male academic workforce</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> in their selecti</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ons</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The social assumptions and norms around gender also have a huge impact. People</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">s understanding of what they</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">re looking for in a surgeon, an engineer, a mathematician or a chemist are also tied up with people</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">s assumptions around gender </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">–</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> the assumed </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">identity of an academic in STEMM tends to be linked to masculinity. This is also similar for leadership roles </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">–</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> the skills or abilities that people think they need in a leader or a manager are also connected to a normative masculine identity, and women who</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> display these skills are often judged negatively because they are perceived to be presenting stereotypically masculine traits. Conversely, women who don</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">t display these traits may be viewed as unsuitable for the role.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">These assumptions can also lead to w</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">omen being given ‘pastoral’ roles within departments, such as teaching and student support roles. This often means that men have more time to focus on research activities – which are more likely to lead to a promotion. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Insecure and u</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">nclear career </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">structure:</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Early career researchers (ECRs) are expected to have completed several </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">fixed-term </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">post</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">doc</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">toral</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> positions before they can progress, and often this means being flexible and able to move </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">frequently or at short notice </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">between different universities</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. ECRs, and women in particular, often say that this is a big disincentive to continuing in academia, especially if they want to stay in one place, or start a family</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Typically, statistical and survey data demonstrates that the biggest barriers are enco</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">unter</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ed when moving from PhD to post-</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">doc</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">toral</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> positions, and from </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">post-</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">doc</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">toral</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> to permanent lecturer positions.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> The career structure is often not made clear to student.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> In addition</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> securing a permanent lecturer job can be difficult for post docs, especia</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">lly if they have little support from their departments or university in preparing their CVs and interviews. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Lack of sponsorship and mentoring:</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Progression is often supported by senior academics who sponsor or informally mentor ECRs. This can be affected </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">by the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">gendered</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">conscious or unconscious </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">biases of senior academics</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, who are predominantly male</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">What this means in practice</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">is </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">that senior male academics </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">may be more likely to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">offer sponsorship to young male ECRs </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">who, unconsciously, remind them of themsel</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ves at an earlier stage in their career, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">while women </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">may</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> not</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> as frequently be afforded</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> the same informal support and encouragement.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Culture:</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The culture of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">particular</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> department</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> also </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">strongly </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">affect</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> whether women will want to continue in academic science. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">A</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> culture of long working hours is very common in academia, and this can act as a disincentive, or simply not be </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">viable,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> for women who are the primary carers of young children or </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">older or disabled r</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">elatives</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Holding core meetings, including professional seminar series and management meetings, outside core hours thus disadvantages scientists with caring responsibilities, of whom a significant majority are women.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Lack of Role Models:</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The lack of femal</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">e role models consciously or unconsciously gives the impression that women can</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">t or don</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">t progress in a particular research area. Having prominent and visible senior and successful women in different fields can have a positive effect not only on women, who</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> may be encouraged and feel it is possible to progress, but also on the public</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">s impression and the stereotypes around STEMM and gender. Greater visibility of women taking lead research roles in STEMM subjects could lead to a larger number of young women c</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">hoosing subjects they don</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">t currently take at A level or University.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">However it should also be noted that </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">very successful women</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> can sometimes act as a disincentive. Women who have succeeded in male dominated fields are often highly motivated and high achie</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">vers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, and may also be able to afford high-quality assistance with caring responsibilities and housework</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. This can lead to a negative response </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">–</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> when women feel that they can only achieve success in particular fields if they are </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">super women</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The pressure </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">on female scientists to act as good role models also adds an extra pressure </span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Lack of support for career breaks</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> and childcare</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">: </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Academic career structures do not accommodate career breaks, for example maternity leave. Success is gauged on </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">research output and this is affected by career breaks and childcare </span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. There are also issues surrounding funding when women leave on maternity and whether research can be paused or covered during their leave.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Activities that are often viewed as essential f</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">or a successful academic career are not possible for primary carers – for example, long working hours culture and international travel for conferences.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> This is something that Universities and funding bodies need to address. Childcare is extremely expensive</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> (especially in London), and Universities need to better support primary careers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> (often women)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">When women leave academia, what careers do they transition into? What are the consequences of scientifically trained women applying their skills in different</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps"> employment sectors?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Women leaving academia are drawn to various jobs and sectors. It is common for women to go to jobs in industry – these positions are often more secure and better paid, especially at junior levels. Women from science also end up in professional support role</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">s in Universities, for example in Human Resources, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">teaching, positions in the NHS, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">administrative roles and research support posts. </span><br /><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The information below has been taken from a project sponsored by UCL, looking into the arguments for a strong focus on equ</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ality and diversity in the Institution. The loss of scientifically trained women leaving academia means that the following key benefits of a diverse workforce will not be realised:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Knowledge production</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">: </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Th</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">e differential access of women and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">men to leadership in the higher education sector not only leads to their underrepresentation, but also influences the nature and process of knowledge production </span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and the ways in which they can influence discourses and practices</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. Rice</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> argues that un</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">iversities have the potential to answer many questions faced in a global society through research, knowledge creation and education. However, universities are often not able to deliver this function effectively due to the quality of the workforce, which ca</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">n inevitably be improved by removing the barriers to inequality. Rice asserts that by not selecting or enabling the ‘best and the brightest’ to perform, universities cannot produce knowledge through creative and cutting-edge research.  This is evident in t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">he claim of the Spanish Minister of Science and Innovation (who supported the law for advancing women in Science, Technology and Innovation): </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 40.2pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">‘A greater presence of women in the world of science and technology is essential for scientific excellence and a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">lso for the economic development of the country’.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Improved performance: </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The literature suggests that a higher representation of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">women</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> at senior management level has a positive effect on the performance of companies</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. Joy et al</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> point out that companies w</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ith a higher number of women on boards have a 42% higher return on sales and 66% higher return on invested capital compared to their competitors with a lower number of women on boards. Huse and Sloberg</span><a name="_ftnref13"></a><a href="#_ftn13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and Izraeli</span><a name="_ftnref14"></a><a href="#_ftn14">[14]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> agree that women take their leadership r</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">oles more seriously than men and prepare more conscientiously for meetings </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">that</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> results in better decisio</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">n making.  McKinsey and Company</span><a name="_ftnref15"></a><a href="#_ftn15">[15]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">suggest that organizations with a third of women in senior management level can produce the best financial results. An</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> evidence for this claim is also </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">found in a Leeds University Business School’s study of female board members. The study</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><a name="_ftnref16"></a><a href="#_ftn16">[16]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> suggests that having one women member on the board decreases the risk of a company going bankrupt by 20% and having two to three decre</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ases the risk further. Moreover, women bring specific strengths to different roles.  McKinsey and Company</span><a name="_ftnref17"></a><a href="#_ftn17">[17]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> argues that women are better at collaborating than men. This can strengthen organizations’ capacity to undertake collaborative work and enter into pa</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">rtnerships for innovative projects. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Problem-solving, decision making and risk </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">management: </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">More equal organizations manage risks and problems more effectively than others</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><a name="_ftnref18"></a><a href="#_ftn18">[18]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. The U</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">K Government Equalities Office</span><a name="_ftnref19"></a><a href="#_ftn19">[19]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> study of public attitudes and perceptions ab</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">out diversity reveals that diverse organizations are more able to deal with problems in a holistic manner compared to institutions with limited diversity.  The report suggests that people with different experiences, lifestyles and backgrounds offer rich pe</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">rspectives and pay greater attention to detail and controlling risks which is not possible in organizations with a less diverse staff</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><a name="_ftnref20"></a><a href="#_ftn20">[20]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Impact on students</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">: </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Research shows that the presence of women professors not only has a significant positive effect </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">on the confidence and self-esteem of female students, but also on that of male students who develop leadership abilities and emotional wellbeing as a result. Sax</span><a name="_ftnref21"></a><a href="#_ftn21">[21]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> analysed how the gender of professors shapes the experiences of male and female students ente</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ring college. Based on survey responses of more than 8 million students who attended University of California, Los Angeles and participated in the Cooperative Institutional Research Program over four decades, Sax concluded: </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 40.2pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">‘Attending institutions with m</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">ore female professors strengthens female students' scholarly confidence, motivation to achieve, and grade-point average. Yet the presence of female professors appears to bring a broader range of benefits to male students, including gains in mathematical co</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">nfidence, scientific orientation, leadership ability, and emotional well-being. An obvious implication of those findings would be for colleges to hire more female faculty members. That could be an opportunity to shape the academic climate, as female facult</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">y members have been shown to be generally more concerned than male faculty members with students' emotional development, character development, and self-understanding’ </span><a name="_ftnref22"></a><a href="#_ftn22">[22]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt 40.2pt 0pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Talent management</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">: </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Davies</span><a name="_ftnref23"></a><a href="#_ftn23">[23]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> asserts that the failure of companies to use the talent of</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> individuals with diverse backgrounds will lead to their underperformance. Women, for example, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">make up a higher proportion of university graduates achieving higher outcomes than men in many areas, and their number in the labour market is steadily increasin</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">g. In such a scenario, if companies do not utilize the talent of women, they will not remain competitive. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Creativity and innovation</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">: </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">E</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">xperts</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> in diversity</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> interviewed for </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">research undertaken by the Institute of Education</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> supported the idea that systems de</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">signed to promote equality, diversity and inclusion within organization lead to enhancing creativity and innovation: </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 40.2pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">‘We benefit in this country from having people from the United States, from Canada….so a mobile academic population is incredibly beneficial,... the benefit is that they provide some cross cultural, cross class, cross ethnicity diversity of cultures.  They</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> expand horizon thinking, forms, views, in and across a variety of different subjects, and that’s true in every respect’</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">(Expert 2)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 57.8pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 40.25pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">‘There’s more creativity.  There’s more debate.  Actually, leading a diverse team isn’t easy because people just don’t go </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">with the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">flow</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">; they sort of question which way you’re flowing.  But actually I think they’re more creative because more people come up with different ideas and perhaps conflicting ideas, but everybody learns.  It’s not just the end result is arguably bette</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">r but everybody learns other people’s ideas and drawing from very, very different experiences.  It’s almost like a win-win</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">’ </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">(Expert 3)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 57.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Improved organizational culture</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">: </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The most tangible and immediate effect of improving diversity is seen in organizational culture.  The effect of diversity practices on organizational culture was also reported by another interviewee: </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 40.25pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">‘We have seen more of the change is more around the cu</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">lture of the organisation. So I think the culture in terms of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">being</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> more family friendly, you know, in terms of looking at how they operate in terms of when meetings take place, in terms of how people feel about protection in terms of research time, when p</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">eople come back from maternity leave.’</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">(Expert 1</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">A diverse workforce might also contribute to the diversity of research aims, approaches and findings. This is not to say that women will have inherently different research interests, but that different pe</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ople will bring different perspectives to research. This is also true for other underrepresented groups. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The decline in female scientists through the academic pipeline reinforces the assumption and stereotypes surrounding science and gender. The conseque</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">nce of this is not only that women coming into the profession might be put off </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">–</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> either through the persistence of a male dominated, male-dominated or macho culture, or through a lack of female role models and sponsors, but this will continue to affirm the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> stereotype that women don</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">t do science. The image of science and who does/doesn</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">t enter, or achieve in science not only might put off young women and girls from choosing science subjects at school, A level and University, but also reinforce public opinion</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and stereotypes. These stereotypes not only, inform how scientists are perceived; who they should be and what people expect from a scientist, but also inform gendered assumptions of what is normal or natural for a boy or girl to be interested in and be go</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">od at. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">What should universities and the higher education sector do to retain women graduates and Ph.D students in academic careers?</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps"> Are there any examples of good </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">practice</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Improve support at key transition points</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">:</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> There should be more support for ECRs </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">–</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> particularly those </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">transitioning between</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> PhD, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">post-doctoral</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and lectureship posts. More needs to be done to encourage and support</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> female</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> ECRs </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">–</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> both in terms of support for applications for funding or positions, but also in the security of positions. Uni</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">versities could look into ways of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ensuring security for </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">post-</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">doc</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">toral</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> fellows </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">because they are the route by which ECR</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">s go on to secure a permanent lecturer post. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Questioni</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ng existing culture and practice:</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Universities need to consider the culture within</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> individual departments and the University as a whole </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">–</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> this might include training in equality and diversity and fair recruitment policies and unconscious bias might help to draw attention to any issues that need addressing. Making sure that there is a su</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">pport network for any member of staff who may experience discrimination is also important </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">–</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> along with a formal system to tackle such issues. Good practices will benefit male and female ECRs alike, but a failure to address the impact of existing culture an</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">d practices will tend to perpetuate the status quo.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Ensuring that staff (men and women at all stages) are encouraged to work flexibly and maintain a healthy work life balance</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">:</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> One of the main issues faced by all academics, which has a particular impact on women who tend to have more caring responsibilities than men, is the long working hours culture within academia. Universities need to try to tackle this to ensure people can w</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ork flexibly. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Such flexibility does not necessarily reduce productivity, but encourages autonomy and resilience of the individual and consequently their overall enjoyment of and commitment to their role.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 50.25pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Examples of good </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">practice</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">:</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">UCL asks that all </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">inter</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">view panels have at least one third</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">female</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> member</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ship</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Anyone who sits on an interview panel has to first attend our fair recruitment briefing</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Unconscious bias training is being rolled out to managers and department</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">al</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> staff across the University </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Under th</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">e new accountability framework, faculties have to submit an equality action plan each year and assess their progress </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">and this is connected to the performance-related pay of senior management</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">UCL offers mentoring and coaching which is available to all staff</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">UCL runs Springboard which women across the university can sign up to</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Female academics returning from maternity leave are offered a 6 month sabbatical in order to focus on their research and be relieved from teaching responsibilities </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">All new staff have t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">o complete online diversity training as a condition of probation</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Paternity leave has been extended to 4 weeks (20 days) paid leave</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">What role should the Government have in encouraging the retention of women in academic STEM careers?</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The link of funding to gender equality schemes such as Athena SWAN has made a significant impact in the number of departments actively working towards gender equality; however it remains to be seen whether this will have a sustained and clear impact on the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> number of women continuing in academic science. The Government should invest more resources in programmes such as Athena SWAN and Project Juno.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The Government could encourage the review of the role of post docs and researchers – several researchers at UC</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">L have suggested that they would be interested in continuing within academia if there were more opportunities for permanent positions, and several have said that they would be interested in a ‘professional post doc’ post. The stress of short fixed term con</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">tracts appears to be a huge disincentive for students and ECRs, and offering more options, or more secure positions might increase interest in an academic career.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The Government could also encourage funding bodies to ask for information on equality and diversity as part of the funding applications process. Moreover, funding bodies not only need to consider the actions undertaken by departments to increase the number</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> of underrepresented groups, but also the gender dimension of research (explained above). </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The Government and research funding bodies should set up stand-alone pots of money for universities and departments who can demonstrate sustained progress on gender</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> equality in order to incentivise action and reward success.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">August 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Moss-Racusin, C. A. et. al. 2012. Science Faculty’s subtle gender biases favour male students. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">PNAS</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">. 109(41) pp. 16474–16</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">479</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#